Risk-tolerance interpretation of the switching threshold.
A foundational clarification: in practice, is never exactly zero. The credal set never literally collapses to a singleton under finite data. The epistemic collapse condition () is a mathematical idealization approached asymptotically, never attained. Consequently, the UKF is always an approximation: it models as aleatory uncertainty that remains partly epistemic. The switching criterion is therefore not “detect when ” but rather: “determine when the UKF’s Gaussian approximation error is acceptable relative to application risk.” The threshold encodes this risk tolerance, and is calibrated via the acceptable false-alarm rate for the NEES consistency test [22]. Choosing a lower (tighter tolerance) switches to ESPF earlier and more often; a higher accepts more Gaussian approximation error in exchange for computational efficiency. This resolves the circularity: one monitors within the UKF regime and switches to ESPF when the approximation risk exceeds the application-calibrated threshold.
